EXPERT TIPS

How To Find the Best Renters Insurance

Jason Metz

Insurance Lead Editor

Amy Danise

Insurance Managing Editor

Michelle Megna

Insurance Lead Editor

Ashlee Valentine

Insurance Editor

Penny Gusner

Insurance Senior Writer

Create a Home Inventory

I suggest you create a home inventory to figure out how much renters insurance you need for your personal property. It can be as simple as creating one with a pen and paper, a spreadsheet, or photos and video on your smartphone. Youâ€™ll then use your home inventory as the baseline to set your personal property coverage.

Jason Metz

Insurance Lead Editor

What Could You Lose in a Lawsuit?

Figuring out how much liability coverage you need can be confusing. Thatâ€™s why I recommend buying enough liability insurance to cover what could be taken from you in a lawsuit. Youâ€™ll want to take assets like bank accounts, real estate and vehicles into account. If you need even more liability insurance, you can also buy an umbrella insurance policy.

Amy Danise

Insurance Managing Editor

Go With Replacement Cost Coverage

I would go with replacement cost coverage over actual cash value coverage. Thatâ€™s because replacement cost coverage doesnâ€™t take depreciation into account and pays to replace your damaged or stolen items with new items. But ACV pays only the value of your damaged or stolen items, minus depreciation. Replacement cost coverage is more expensive than ACV, but itâ€™s much better coverage.

Michelle Megna

Insurance Lead Editor

Schedule Your Jewelry and Other High-Value Items

Iâ€™d encourage you to schedule high-value items like jewelry. Thatâ€™s because renters insurance policies have â€œspecial limitsâ€ for stolen jewelry, such as $1,500. That wonâ€™t go very far if a thief swipes your $5,000 engagement ring. Scheduling personal property like artwork, collectibles and musical instruments covers your items for their full value.

Ashlee Valentine

How to Find the Best Renters Insurance for Different Situations

Your particular living circumstances may affect the renters insurance you choose.

The personal liability portion of a renters insurance policy pays the medical costs of others if your pet injures them. It can also pay for property damage caused by your pet and your legal fees if someone sues you. Some companies exclude coverage for certain dog breeds. If that impacts you, look for a separate dog liability insurance policy or switch insurance companies. 

You Have a Roommate 

Many renters insurance companies require roommates to have their own separate policies. Given the relatively low cost of coverage, it can be beneficial to have your own policy even if your state and insurer allow you to share renters insurance with a roommate. You wonâ€™t have to change your policy if your roommate moves out, and youâ€™ll only be responsible for claims you make. 

Youâ€™re a College Student  

If you rent a house or apartment off-campus, your landlord may require you to have renters insurance. Even if it isnâ€™t required, renters insurance for college students has advantages. Buying a policy means you can be compensated if your belongings are damaged or stolen. What Is Renters Insurance?

Renters insurance is a type of insurance specifically designed to meet the needs of tenants. Itâ€™s important because a landlordâ€™s insurance covers the building itself, not your belongings. Without renters insurance, youâ€™d have to pay to replace all your possessions if a fire, tornado or other disaster rips through the building.

Beyond covering your belongings, renters insurance also includes liability coverage and insurance for additional living expenses. Plus, coverage for guest medical payments can pay out for minor injuries to guests (typically up to $1,000), no matter whoâ€™s responsible for the injury.

What Does Renters Insurance Cover?

Renters insurance covers your personal belongings and also includes other valuable coverage types. Hereâ€™s what youâ€™ll find in a standard renters insurance policy:

  • Personal property coverage: This includes your belongings such as furniture, jewelry, rugs, clothing, kitchenware and electronics for problems like theft, fire, smoke and vandalism. 
  • Liability insurance: This pays for accidental property damage and injuries caused to others. For example, if someone falls in your apartment, your liability can pay their medical bills and your legal costs if you get sued. 
  • Medical payments to others: This coverage pays for smaller medical bills, no matter who was at fault for the accident, like if your guest slips in your apartment and suffers a minor injury. This coverage is usually sold in small amounts, such as $1,000. 
  • Additional living expenses: If you canâ€™t live in your home because of a problem covered by your policy (like a fire), this pays for costs like hotel bills, restaurant meals and pet boarding fees. Additional living expenses coverage is also referred to as loss of use. 

Does Renters Insurance Cover Roommates?

You can share renters insurance with roommates if your insurance company and state allow it. Youâ€™ll need to list your roommateâ€™s name as an insured on your renters insurance policy.

Many renters insurance companies require roommates to have their own policies. That means your roommate wonâ€™t be covered under your policy if their belongings are stolen or destroyed by a problem such as a fire.

Is Renters Insurance Worth It?

Renters insurance can be worth it and is an affordable way to cover personal belongings, and donâ€™t forget about its liability insurance and coverage for additional living expenses.

Here are common scenarios that renters insurance can cover:

  • Your personal belongings are destroyed. In a worst case scenario, like a fire, renters insurance will pay to replace your stuff. Itâ€™s a good idea to buy â€œreplacement cost coverageâ€ with your renters policy, so youâ€™re reimbursed for buying new items, not the depreciated value of what you lost.
  • Your personal belongings are stolen. Renters insurance covers items stolen inside and outside your home. For example, if someone steals your luggage from a hotel room, thatâ€™s covered.
  • You own high-value items. If you own expensive items such as jewelry, art or musical instruments, renters insurance can pay to replace them if they are stolen or damaged by a problem covered by your policy. You may need to â€œscheduleâ€ certain types of items if your policy has sub-limits. For example, a renters insurance policy might have a $1,000 limit for stolen jewelry.
  • Someone gets hurt while visiting your home. Accidents happen. If someone gets hurt in your home and youâ€™re legally liable, renters insurance will cover medical bills, legal costs and judgments.
  • You have a dog. If your dog bites someoneâ€”whether inside your apartment or away from homeâ€”you could suffer a major financial setback without renters insurance. Liability coverage within renters insurance can cover lawsuits like this.
  • You need money to live elsewhere if your apartment is being repaired. Coverage for additional living expenses pays extra costs such as hotel bills and restaurant meals if you canâ€™t live at home because of a problem covered by the policy. For example, if you have to live in a hotel after a fire, you can get reimbursed.

How Do I file a Renters Insurance Claim? 

Filing a renters insurance claim is fairly straightforward, but there are a couple of things to do before notifying your insurance company. First, contact your landlord to inform them of any situation. If theft is involved, youâ€™ll need to file a police report next, as your insurer will require that for a theft claim.

After these steps, promptly notify your insurance company. Insurers typically have claims forms for you to fill out. Many companies have the form available online or through their mobile apps. Here, youâ€™ll share information on your damage or loss and whether you need temporary housing. An adjuster may visit to review the damage and loss. Your insurer will then decide what payment will be offered. You can appeal a decision if you feel that you should get more.

Best Renters Insurance Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)

Can a landlord require renters insurance?

Some landlords require tenants to purchase renters insurance to avoid potential liability claims from renters due to damaged property from problems such as fire. Theft is another reason, as without renters insurance to cover your losses, you may try to sue the landlord for failing to protect the property.

Landlords who require renters insurance often include a clause in the lease. For example, a lease might state that the renter must provide proof of renters insurance within 14 days of the first day of the lease.

Should I bundle renters and car insurance?

You can often land a discount by bundling auto and renters insurance, and youâ€™ll typically have the convenience of managing both policies from a single account. But bundling renters and car insurance isnâ€™t necessarily the best move.

You might find better prices by purchasing your car insurance and renters insurance from different companies. Thatâ€™s why itâ€™s a good idea to compare renters and car insurance quotes. And bundling wonâ€™t be the best fit if the insurer doesnâ€™t sell the coverage you want. For example, not all auto insurers offer accident forgiveness coverage.

Does renters insurance cover theft?

Renters insurance covers theft of personal belongings both inside and outside your home. A renters insurance will only pay up to your policy limits you have chosen. For example, if you have $20,000 worth of coverage, it will only pay up to that amount. You can buy higher policy limits.

Renters insurance has what are called â€œspecial limitsâ€ for certain types of items. For example, your policy might only cover $1,000 for stolen jewelry. That wonâ€™t cut it for expensive items such as a valuable watch. You can â€œscheduleâ€ valuable items, which provides extra coverage.

Do college students need renters insurance?

Renters insurance for college students can be a wise decision if a college student lives off campus, such as an apartment, and who owns expensive items. If the student lives on campus, such as a dorm, parentsâ€™ homeowners insurance will likely cover their personal property.

If your college student lives in a dorm, find out if your home insurance policy has a limit on coverage for personal property in your childâ€™s dorm, such as 10%â€”which is generally more than sufficient. For example, if you have a $100,000 personal property limit, your childâ€™s belongings in a dorm room will be covered up to $10,000.
